response:
The pre-initiative docs snapshot is empty, so I'll reason from the described stack (Next.js 16, Payload CMS 3 / Lexical, Tailwind 4, Elan design system) and the exact symptoms you described. Let me give you a complete, precise diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

Two distinct, compounding problems:

1. **Bold abuse** — the source markdown used `**…**` inline spans as pseudo-labels ("Per user.", "Scaffolding.", "Key insight:") — a scan-anchor pattern authors use in drafts. Lexical stored every one of those as a `bold` format leaf. The renderer faithfully outputs them as `<strong>`, giving 36 bold spans scattered through body prose. None of them signal *semantic* importance; they are navigational crutches that should not survive publication.

2. **Weak section separation** — the essay has 7 top-level sections. Without a strong vertical rhythm cue between them the eye conflates them. Likely cause: the section wrapper applies only paragraph spacing inherited from `prose`, so `<h2>` sits at normal paragraph distance from the preceding body text with no deliberate above-clearance, and no visual device (rule, extra space, or label) reinforces the break.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Author-intent leakage through serialization** (draft formatting semantics surfacing in published output because the rich-text serializer has no suppression layer for non-semantic bold).

**EAP-027 — Prose rhythm collapse** (section headers styled only by font size, without dedicated top-margin tokens, causing visual grouping failure when body text and the next heading are perceived as one block).

---

## Fix

There are three files to touch.

---

### 1. Strip non-semantic bold at the serializer level

Payload 3 uses Lexical. Bold is stored as a `format` bitmask on text nodes (`IS_BOLD = 1`). The standard practice is a custom serializer component. The right place to intercept is whichever file renders `SerializedLexicalNode` trees — typically called something like `RichText.tsx`, `LexicalRenderer.tsx`, or `serialize.tsx`.

**`src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx`** (or your equivalent path)

```tsx
// BEFORE — naive pass-through
case 'text': {
  let text = <span key={i}>{node.text}</span>
  if (node.format & IS_BOLD)   text = <strong key={i}>{text}</strong>
  if (node.format & IS_ITALIC) text = <em key={i}>{text}</em>
  return text
}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — introduce a context flag that paragraphs can set
// Add this constant at the top of the file:
const PROSE_BOLD_STRIP = true // strip bold from body paragraphs; allow it only in headings/callouts

// Inside the text-node case:
case 'text': {
  const isBold   = !!(node.format & IS_BOLD)
  const isItalic = !!(node.format & IS_ITALIC)
  const isCode   = !!(node.format & IS_CODE)

  let el: React.ReactNode = node.text

  // Only honour bold when it is inside a heading or an explicit callout block.
  // In ordinary paragraph context it was almost certainly a draft scan-anchor.
  if (isBold && !ctx.insideHeading && PROSE_BOLD_STRIP) {
    // Demote to italic — preserves mild emphasis without the scan-anchor weight
    el = <em key={i} className="not-bold-emphasis">{el}</em>
  } else if (isBold) {
    el = <strong key={i}>{el}</strong>
  }

  if (isItalic) el = <em key={i}>{el}</em>
  if (isCode)   el = <code key={i}>{el}</code>
  return el
}
```

Pass `ctx.insideHeading = true` when you recurse into heading nodes:

```tsx
case 'heading': {
  const Tag = node.tag  // 'h1' | 'h2' | 'h3'
  return (
    <Tag key={i}>
      {node.children.map((child, ci) =>
        serializeNode(child, ci, { ...ctx, insideHeading: true })
      )}
    </Tag>
  )
}
```

> **Why demote to `<em>` rather than drop entirely?** The author's intent was *"this phrase matters"*. Italic preserves a whisper of that without hammering the eye on every scan. If your editorial policy is stricter, change `<em>` to a plain `<span>` with no decoration.

---

### 2. Harden section separation in the prose Tailwind config

**`src/styles/prose.css`** (or wherever your `@layer components` prose overrides live; could also be `tailwind.config.ts` under `typography`)

```css
/* BEFORE — typical defaults */
.prose h2 {
  /* only font-size / font-weight from @tailwindcss/typography */
}
```

```css
/* AFTER — give h2 a deliberate breathing zone */
@layer components {
  .prose h2 {
    /* Tailwind 4 uses CSS custom properties directly */
    margin-top: var(--spacing-16);   /* 4rem — hard break from the preceding body */
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-4); /* 1rem — tight to the content it owns       */
    padding-top: var(--spacing-6);   /* additional optical lift                   */
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle); /* thin rule as visual anchor */
  }

  /* First h2 should not have a rule above it — it follows the lede, not a section */
  .prose h2:first-of-type {
    border-top: none;
    padding-top: 0;
    margin-top: var(--spacing-10);
  }
}
```

If you are using the `@tailwindcss/typography` plugin, the same effect goes into `tailwind.config.ts`:

```ts
// tailwind.config.ts
typography: (theme) => ({
  DEFAULT: {
    css: {
      h2: {
        marginTop:    theme('spacing.16'),   // 4rem
        marginBottom: theme('spacing.4'),    // 1rem
        paddingTop:   theme('spacing.6'),
        borderTopWidth: '1px',
        borderTopColor: theme('colors.border.subtle'),  // map to your Elan token
      },
      'h2:first-of-type': {
        borderTopWidth: '0',
        paddingTop: '0',
        marginTop: theme('spacing.10'),
      },
    },
  },
}),
```

---

### 3. Add a section-label utility class in the Elan token layer (optional but strongly recommended)

If the Elan system has a concept of *"section metadata"* (e.g., section number, chapter label), surface it here instead of relying on visual weight alone:

**`src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx`** — heading serialization:

```tsx
case 'heading': {
  if (node.tag === 'h2') {
    return (
      <div key={i} className="essay-section">
        <h2 className="essay-section__heading">
          {node.children.map((child, ci) =>
            serializeNode(child, ci, { ...ctx, insideHeading: true })
          )}
        </h2>
      </div>
    )
  }
  // h3, h4 … unchanged
}
```

**`src/styles/essay.css`**

```css
@layer components {
  .essay-section {
    margin-top: var(--spacing-16);
  }

  .essay-section__heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: var(--font-semibold);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    color: var(--color-foreground);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-4);
  }

  /* rule sits between section wrapper and heading */
  .essay-section::before {
    content: '';
    display: block;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--color-border-subtle);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-6);
  }
}
```

---

## Summary of changes

| File | What changes | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx` | Bold text nodes in paragraph context → `<em>`, not `<strong>` | Kills the 36 draft scan-anchors without discarding author intent |
| `serialize.tsx` heading branch | Pass `ctx.insideHeading = true` when recursing | Preserves intentional bold in actual headings |
| `src/styles/prose.css` or `tailwind.config.ts` | `h2` gets `margin-top: 4rem`, `padding-top: 1.5rem`, `border-top` | Creates hard visual break, establishes clear hierarchy |
| `src/styles/essay.css` + `.essay-section` wrapper | Optional semantic wrapper with `::before` rule | Elan-idiomatic approach that separates structure from type scale |

---

## Principle

**Never let draft formatting semantics survive into the serialization layer.** Bold in Lexical (or any rich-text store) carries the meaning the *author* intended *at the time of writing*, not necessarily what a *reader* needs to see. A serializer is the correct choke-point to enforce publication-quality typography rules — not the CMS, and not the CSS. Suppressing non-semantic bold in paragraph context (AP-072) and giving headings an explicit vertical rhythm token (EAP-027) are two halves of the same contract: *structure is communicated by space and hierarchy, not by weight.*
